This Thanksgiving, the Hunt family wants to share a heartfelt message of gratitude and reflection.

Children are among life‚Äôs greatest blessings. Their laughter, innocence, and boundless energy remind us of what truly matters and bring unparalleled joy to our lives. 

Victoria, Olivia, and Willie are the light of our family, and we are endlessly thankful for them each day.

As we gather with loved ones, let us also hold in our hearts those who cannot be with their families this holiday season‚Äîespecially the brave men and women serving in our military.

May we all cherish the moments that matter most and extend kindness and gratitude to those around us.

Happy Thanksgiving from the Hunt Family!

Name: Sanders, Bernard
text:
This time of year, I am always reminded of the Thanksgiving scene painted by one of my favorite artists, Norman Rockwell. Many people don‚Äôt know this, but Rockwell actually lived for a time in Arlington, Vermont, and painted some of his most well-known pieces there, including his ‚ÄúFour Freedoms.‚Äù He even used many of his Vermont neighbors as models and inspiration in his work.

Rockwell‚Äôs ‚ÄúFour Freedoms‚Äù series was published in the Saturday Evening Post in 1943. They were paintings that reflected the vision that President Franklin Delano Roosevelt articulated in his 1941 State of the Union speech: Freedom of Speech, Freedom of Worship, Freedom from Want, and Freedom from Fear.  

In that speech Roosevelt stated:

‚ÄúIn the future days, which we seek to make secure, we look forward to a world founded upon four essential human freedoms.

‚ÄúThe first is freedom of speech and expression‚Äîeverywhere in the world.

‚ÄúThe second is freedom of every person to worship God in his own way‚Äîeverywhere in the world.

‚ÄúThe third is freedom from want‚Äîwhich, translated into world terms, means economic understandings which will secure to every nation a healthy peacetime life for its inhabitants‚Äîeverywhere in the world.

‚ÄúThe fourth is freedom from fear‚Äîwhich, translated into world terms, means a world-wide reduction of armaments to such a point and in such a thorough fashion that no nation will be in a position to commit an act of physical aggression against any neighbor‚Äîanywhere in the world.

‚ÄúThat is no vision of a distant millennium. It is a definite basis for a kind of world attainable in our own time and generation. That kind of world is the very antithesis of the so-called new order of tyranny which the dictators seek to create with the crash of a bomb.‚Äù

In my view, Roosevelt‚Äôs vision from 1941 remains relevant today.

On behalf of Jane, my children, and my grandkids, let me take this opportunity to wish everybody a very happy Thanksgiving and a wonderful holiday season.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district, individuals whose extraordinary efforts uplift our community and inspire us. Today, we shine a spotlight on a Bucks County native working to change lives‚Äîmeet Taylor Kreiling, founder of Dream Drive.
 
While Taylor has a successful career in Healthcare IT, her true calling lies in advocating for the well-being of children and families in need. Recognizing the pressing need to support underprivileged families year-round, especially children in foster care, Taylor founded Dream Drive in 2012. What began as a small effort with 25 volunteers has grown into a robust, community-wide network that has touched the lives of hundreds of children and families across Bucks County.
 
For the past nine years, Dream Drive has ensured that over 300 children experience the joy of Christmas‚Äîproviding gifts, festive celebrations, and the invaluable opportunity to create lasting memories filled with love and care. Furthermore, Taylor's mission extends beyond the holiday season; it is a year-round commitment of support. Dream Drive provides vital hygiene kits, backpacks filled with school supplies, pantry essentials, birthday celebrations, and seasonal care packages. But perhaps the most important part of her work is the unwavering support she provides to teens aging out of the foster care system‚Äîa vulnerable group often left to navigate adulthood without guidance or resources. Dream Drive provides tools and support to transition into independence and a brighter future. Taylor is also a fierce advocate for mental health awareness within the foster care system, partnering with organizations to bring about meaningful change.
 
Please join me in applauding Taylor Kreiling for her extraordinary dedication and selfless service to our community. She has sparked a transformative movement of inspiring hope, lifting spirits, changing lives, and creating a ripple of generosity throughout our community. Thank you, Taylor, you are a true Hometown Hero.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1954, a meteorite struck Ann Hodges in Sylacauga, Alabama, making her the first person ever injured by a meteorite. 

The rock, weighing 8.5 pounds, crashed through the roof, hitting Hodges in the hip while she napped on her couch, causing a bruise. The event became a media sensation, and a year-long legal battle ensued over ownership of the meteorite. Although it was initially sent to the Smithsonian, Alabama congressman Kenneth Roberts intervened, and it was eventually returned to the state.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 2001, Enron Corporation filed for bankruptcy, marking the beginning of one of the largest corporate scandals in U.S. history.

Founded in 1985 through the merger of Houston Natural Gas and Internorth, Enron quickly grew into a major energy-trading company. Under CEO Kenneth Lay, the company reached #7 on Fortune's list of the top 500 U.S. companies by 2000, employing 21,000 people and generating $111 billion in revenue. However, by the end of the year, Enron‚Äôs stock price had plummeted from $90.75 in August to just $0.26 by November. As the stock dropped, Lay sold off his shares while encouraging employees to buy more, leading many to lose their retirement savings. The company‚Äôs collapse was triggered when a planned $8.4 billion buyout by Dynegy fell through, and Enron filed for bankruptcy.

Enron‚Äôs fall was later linked to widespread accounting fraud, where it hid debts and losses through off-the-books partnerships. This prompted investigations by the SEC and Justice Department, revealing that Lay and CEO Jeffrey Skilling had conspired to mislead investors about the company‚Äôs financial health. The scandal also implicated Arthur Andersen, Enron‚Äôs auditor, which was found guilty of destroying incriminating documents. Although Andersen‚Äôs conviction was later overturned, the damage to its reputation led to the firm's downfall.

In 2004, Skilling and Lay were indicted and convicted on multiple charges, including fraud and insider trading. The trial saw former executives, including CFO Andrew Fastow, testify against Lay and Skilling. Fastow had pleaded guilty to conspiracy charges and cooperated with prosecutors. Lay died of heart disease shortly after the verdict, leading to the dismissal of charges against him. Skilling, sentenced to over 24 years in prison, served about 12 years before his release in 2019.

Enron‚Äôs collapse cost billions, destroyed thousands of jobs, and became a symbol of corporate fraud, ultimately leading to stricter regulations like the Sarbanes-Oxley Act.

These days, academics are teaching only the trendy ‚Äúcounter-narratives.‚Äù Instead of focusing first on teaching the mainstream story of history, they partake in this faux noble cause by teaching only the counter-narratives.

Understanding counter-narratives and opposing views can help develop critical thinking skills. The problem, however, is that they‚Äôre the *only* things many teachers are teaching. Students are left with an incomplete and biased view of history.

That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm supporting the Crucial Communism Teaching Act, which directs the Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation to create a civic education curriculum and oral history resources for high school students. This initiative will give students an honest understanding of ideologies like communism and totalitarianism that directly conflict with the principles of America.

Communism isn‚Äôt a utopia‚Äîit‚Äôs a system of misery, oppression, and countless lives lost. We can‚Äôt let the next generation grow up without understanding this.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1989 during a historic summit off the coast of Malta, President George Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev make statements suggesting that the Cold War's longstanding tensions are coming to an end. 

The summit, the first between the two leaders, was viewed with cautious optimism by Bush and his advisers, who were eager to build on the arms control progress made during the Reagan administration. Gorbachev, however, was more outspoken, emphasizing his desire for better U.S.-Soviet relations to support his domestic reforms. He declared that the Cold War's defining elements‚Äîarms races, mistrust, and ideological conflict‚Äîshould be left behind. Bush, while more reserved, expressed hope that the U.S. and Soviet Union could usher in a new era of cooperation, particularly in ending the division of Europe.

Despite the optimistic rhetoric, the summit yielded few concrete outcomes. Both leaders agreed to work toward a treaty on nuclear and conventional arms by 1990 and planned a follow-up summit for June 1990 in Washington, D.C.

Name: Peters, Scott H.
text:
I‚Äôve listened and thought a lot about the Hunter Biden pardon. It was the wrong thing to do.

I sympathize with a father who rightly believes his son has been targeted by a politically motivated prosecution.  And many prosecutors ‚Äì most are elected ‚Äì have political motives. But prosecutors don‚Äôt adjudicate guilt ‚Äì juries do, beyond a reasonable doubt, according to the law, and subject to appeal.  Hunter Biden made his mistakes, and he should have faced his consequences, with all the many protections our system provides.

We elected Joe Biden to put the country and the rule of law ahead of himself and his family.  When we rightly criticize Trump for pardoning Stone, Bannon, Flynn, Kushner, and his Jan 6 rioters, Republicans will now just reply that Biden pardoned Hunter. This is how the fragile norms that support our nation of laws change. The shoes are on both feet.

But listen up, Senators: If you don‚Äôt like presidential policies that put family and political cronies over country, you have the power to uphold the standard of law Americans have a right to expect. You may feel that Biden politized the justice system. Trump has explicitly said he will use that system to attack his political enemies. Don‚Äôt approve appointees for Attorney General and the FBI who will allow that to happen. Please keep our rule of law the envy of the world.
